{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.06,0.02,0.86]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47453"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/818"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32169"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9137"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43821"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47453"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent and painless passage of blood per rectum. This occurs mainly at the time he uses his bowels and is streaked on the surface of the faeces. He notices blood dripping into the pan after defaecation. He has never had these symptoms before. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perianal haematoma","Anal squamous cell carcinoma","Diverticular bleed","Inflammatory bowel disease","Internal haemorrhoids"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal haemorrhoids\u003C/strong\u003E are due to a prolapse of anal mucosa originating above the dentate line associated with the superior haemorrhoidal plexus. Due to their anatomical origin, they present as painless, intermittent, frank bleeding on the outside of the stool or on toilet paper.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms is bleeding from internal haemorrhoids, the possibility of an underlying malignancy must always be considered. For reasons that are not clear, colorectal cancers are now occurring in younger age groups. They are frequently associated with a relatively poor prognosis - largely because the symptoms are ignored both by the patient and the doctor on the assumption that the bleeding is from haemorrhoids. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnal squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a painful, ulcerated lesion on the anal margin. Bleeding and discharge may also occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerianal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as external haemorrhoids, are dilated anal veins covered by skin below the dentate line. They are often extremely painful, preceded by a period of excessive straining. A tender, palpable, blue subcutaneous mass on the anal margin adjacent to the anal canal can be found.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticular bleed\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential to consider in painless per rectum bleeding, especially in older patients. However, it would be unusual in a 35-year-old patient with no other risk factors or symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E such as Crohn\u0027s disease or ulcerative colitis can present with bloody diarrhea. However, additional symptoms like abdominal pain, weight loss, and extra-intestinal manifestations are usually present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Internal haemorrhoids are a prominent cause of intermittent, painless per rectum bleeding.","The possibility of an underlying malignancy should be considered in the presentation of per rectum bleeding, even in the presence of haemorrhoids on physical examination (particularly if not visualised to be actively bleeding).","The presentation of internal haemorrhoids can be explained anatomically, as they originate above the dentate line."],"references":["Garden OJ, Bradbury AW, Forsythe JLR, Parks RW. Davidson\u2019s Principles and Practice of Surgery. 6th edition. 2012. Philadelphia: Churchill Livingstone Elsevier","Bailey H, Capper W, Love R, Rains A. Bailey and Love\u0027s short practice of surgery. 2008. London: H.K. Lewis.","Mohammed Ilyas MI, Szilagy EJ. Management of Diverticular Bleeding: Evaluation, Stabilization, Intervention, and Recurrence of Bleeding and Indications for Resection after Control of Bleeding. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2018;31(4):243-250. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29942215/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32169"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32169"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-23T19:59:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-02T14:27:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"818"}},"conten